# üêû bug report

### Affected Package
<!-- Can you pin-point one or more @angular/* packages as the source of the bug? -->
<!-- ‚úçÔ∏èedit: --> Unsure. I attempted to reproduce using ExtractTextPlugin, OptimizeCssAssetsPlugin, css-loader and cssnano but was unable to reproduce the behavior outside of an Angular project.


### Is this a regression?

<!-- Did this behavior use to work in the previous version? -->
<!-- ‚úçÔ∏è--> No.


### Description

<!-- ‚úçÔ∏è-->
In certain situations, multiple media queries for different classes are being combined into one which can change the order of css, breaking css-variable behavior.

Here is the pattern:

~~~~
/* First media query for an unrelated class at a certain width */
@media (min-width: 48em) {
  .unrelated-class-share-media-query-1 {
      font-size: 5px;
  }

}

/* It only happens in my build when there is some other css in between the first media query and the variable definition */
.filler-class-1 {
  font-size: 15px;
}

/* Class that defines variable */
.variable-definition {
    --num-columns: 1;
    --col-width: calc(100%/var(--num-columns));

}

.class-that-uses-variable {
    flex-basis: var(--col-width);
}

/* Second media query of same width that changes the variable*/
@media (min-width: 48em) {
    .variable-definition {
        --num-columns: 3;
    }
}
~~~~

This outputs:

~~~~
@media (min-width:48em) {
	.unrelated-class-share-media-query-1[_ngcontent-uni-c0] {
		font-size: 5px
	}
	.variable-definition[_ngcontent-uni-c0] {
		--num-columns: 3
	}
}

.filler-class-1[_ngcontent-uni-c0] {
	font-size: 15px
}

.variable-definition[_ngcontent-uni-c0] {
	--num-columns: 1;
	--col-width: calc(100%/var(--num-columns))
}

.class-that-uses-variable[_ngcontent-uni-c0] {
	flex-basis: var(--col-width)
}

~~~~

This causes the value of `--num-columns` to be 1 when it should be 3, because of the reordering.


